The tumor cells are positive for Pax-8 and negative for p63, supporting the diagnosis of renal cell carcinoma.  The malignant cells are similar to those seen in the patient's recent left ilium FNA (\R\cf. C12-45508).  The cytologic and architectural features, in conjunction with the immunostains performed on the cell block material from the FNA, are most consistent with a papillary renal cell carcinoma.  However, negative staining for CK7 precludes a definitive diagnosis of the papillary subtype on this limited material, and an unclassified renal cell carcinoma remains in the differential.

Tumor measures 6.0 cm in greatest dimension.  Carcinoma invades perinephric fat, renal sinus fat, and the renal  vein.  Tumor is present at both the renal vein as well as the soft  tissue surgical resection margins.  Extensive angiolymphatic invasion by tumor is identified.  Two lymph nodes are negative for metastatic carcinoma (0/2).  Adrenal gland with no significant pathologic diagnosis.  Accessory spleen with no significant pathologic diagnosis.

Renal cell carcinoma, clear cell type, with focal sarcomatoid transformation. All surgical margins, including the ureteral and vascular margins, are free of tumor.      Adjacent kidney shows mild non-specific chronic pyelonephritis. B. Lymph nodes, paracaval (excision): Benign fibroadipose tissue. No lymph nodes identified (0/0).

pathology_report: The tumor cells are diffusely positive for CD34 and focally  positive for CD117 and SMA.  They are negative for HMB45,  Melan-A, and Pax-8. Juxtaglomerular cell tumors are rare kidney tumors that  typically have an indolent clinical course.  However, a single  instance of metastasis has been reported in the literature, thus  precluding a completely benign diagnosis.  Features suggestive of  malignant potential have not been described in these tumors,  though features suggestive of malignancy in other neoplasms are  absent in this tumor (i.e., necrosis, vascular invasion, high  mitotic rate, atypical mitotic figures, large size).  While there  is focal moderate nuclear atypia, this has been reported in  otherwise benign reninomas and is favored to be atypia of the  'endocrine-type' as seen in other benign endocrine neoplasms

Because of the coexistence of low (Fuhrmann grade 2)adjacent to high grade clear cell carcinoma (Fuhrman grade 4), the possibility of translocation carcinoma is considered.  This tumor is positive for CA-9 and Vimentin and is negative for CK AE1/AE3, CK7, Melan-A, and HMB45.  This staining is consistent with a clear cell carcinoma and does not favor a translocation type tumor. Tumor invades into but not through renal capsule. No vascular or peripelvic invasion is identified. All surgical margins are negative for carcinoma. Marked perinephric fibrosis with chronic inflammation. Non-neoplastic renal parenchyma is histologically unremarkable

pathology_report: Renal cell carcinoma, unclassified type, with sarcomatoid  differentiation (ISUP nucleolar grade 4).  Tumor measures 2.5 cm in greatest dimension grossly (per report).  Carcinoma invades perinephric fat (pT3a).  No definite angiolymphatic invasion identified.  Tumor is present at the deep renal parenchymal margin and abuts  the perinephric fat margin. The tumor is composed of epithelioid cells arranged in  nests and sheets with areas of spindle cell (sarcomatoid) growth  (approximately 10-20% of the tumor).  The cytoplasm is generally  eosinophilic (not clear), and the classic 'chicken-wire'  vasculature of a conventional clear cell renal cell carcinoma is  not present. Immunohistochemical stains performed at  NYP/WCM show that the  tumor cells are positive for Pax-8 and negative for GATA-3,  supporting the diagnosis of renal cell carcinoma.  CK7 shows only  rare positive cells.  CA-IX staining is patchy, and the staining  pattern/distribution is felt to most likely represent  ischemic/hypoxic upregulation rather than intrinsic dysregulation  of the pathway within the tumor cells.   Overall, the morphologic and immunohistochemical profile are not  diagnostic of any defined renal cell carcinoma subtype.

pathology_report: Poorly differentiated carcinoma, consistent with metastatic  renal carcinoma.   Note: IHC is PAX- 8 and AE1/AE3 positive and negative for WT-1,  Calretinin, CK5/6, CK7, GATA-3, CD31 and CD34.  This profile is  consistent with a conventional renal cell carcinoma.  Papillary  renal cell carcinoma and carcinomas of gynecological origin can  be PAX-8 positive, but other markers (CK7 ad WT-1 negative) are  against those diagnoses.

pathology_report: Lymph node, supraclavicular, biopsy; The tumor is composed of papillary structures lined by  eosinophilic cells with enlarged nuclei and prominent nuclei.  The morphology is similar to that seen in the prior Level 7 lymph  node FNA performed at NYPH (C15-39778), and that tumor showed an  immunohistochemical staining pattern most consistent with a renal  cell carcinoma (positive for Pax-8 and negative for GATA-3 and  p63).  (Per report, the tumor cells in this material are positive  for pan-CK and negative for CK7, CK20, CEA, CA19-9, and TTF-1.)

Path revealed an 11.9 cm clear-cell renal cell carcinoma, nuclear grade 3, extending into the renal pelvis with renal vein invasion.  Tumor was present at the renal vein margin as well as the renal vein lumen excision (T3).  Additionally 6/26 lymph nodes were involved by tumor.  Adrenal gland was not involved.
